      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(telegram): suppress reconnect drain re-entry while delivery is in-flight",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nWhen a live Telegram send stalls (e.g. 129 seconds as reported in #89953), every subsequent `poll-success` event triggers a reconnect drain that finds the same pending delivery already claimed by the in-flight send. The drain returns immediately, clears the `#deliveryDrainInFlight` guard, and the next poll re-triggers the cycle. This produces repeated \"already being recovered\" log entries every ~30 seconds until the stalled send completes.\n\n## Root cause\n\nTwo separate in-flight tracking mechanisms interact:\n\n1. `#deliveryDrainInFlight` in `TelegramPollingSession`: prevents concurrent drain calls, but resets as soon as the drain function returns.\n2. `entriesInProgress` in `delivery-queue-recovery.ts`: tracks individual entries claimed by live sends via `withActiveDeliveryClaim`.\n\nWhen the live send holds an entry via `withActiveDeliveryClaim` (in `deliver.ts`), the drain function quickly skips the entry (\"already being recovered\"), returns, and clears the session-level guard. The next poll success starts a fresh drain that again finds the same claimed entry.\n\n## Fix\n\n1. **`delivery-queue-recovery.ts`**: `drainPendingDeliveries` now returns a `ReconnectDrainResult` with `{ matched, drained, skippedInProgress }` counts instead of `void`.\n\n2. **`polling-session.ts`**: When the drain result shows all matched entries were skipped due to in-progress claims (`skippedInProgress > 0 && drained === 0`), the session sets a 30-second cooldown before allowing the next drain attempt.\n\nThis eliminates the repeated log noise and wasted I/O from futile drain attempts while preserving the ability to drain genuinely new entries as soon as the cooldown expires or in-flight sends complete.\n\n## Changed files\n\n| File | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| `src/infra/outbound/delivery-queue-recovery.ts` | Add `ReconnectDrainResult` type; track `skippedInProgress`/`drained` counters in `drainPendingDeliveries`; return the result |\n| `src/infra/outbound/delivery-queue.ts` | Re-export `ReconnectDrainResult` type |\n| `src/plugin-sdk/delivery-queue-runtime.ts` | Pass through `ReconnectDrainResult` return type |\n| `extensions/telegram/src/polling-session.ts` | Add `#deliveryDrainCooldownUntil` field and `DELIVERY_DRAIN_COOLDOWN_MS` constant; check cooldown in `#drainPendingDeliveriesAfterReconnect`; set cooldown when all entries are in-progress |\n\n## Tests\n\n- 3 new tests in `delivery-queue.reconnect-drain.test.ts`: verify drain result reports `skippedInProgress` for claimed entries, `drained` for recovered entries, and empty result for no matches\n- 2 new tests in `polling-session.test.ts`: verify drain re-entry is suppressed when all entries are in-progress, and NOT suppressed when entries are actually drained\n- All 69 existing + new tests pass\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- **Behavior or issue addressed:** Telegram reconnect drain re-enters on every poll-success (~30s interval) while a live send holds the pending delivery via `withActiveDeliveryClaim`, producing repeated \"already being recovered\" log messages and wasted I/O until the stall resolves (129s observed in #89953).\n- **Real environment tested:** macOS 15.5 (darwin 25.5.0), Node v26.0.0, OpenClaw built from patched source at `/tmp/wt-90066` (commit e58f5a571c).\n- **Exact steps or command run after this patch:**\n\n  Step 1. Built from the patched branch:\n  ```bash\n  cd /tmp/wt-90066\n  pnpm install --frozen-lockfile\n  pnpm build\n  ```\n\n  Step 2. Verified the cooldown guard and drain result tracking are active in the production bundle:\n  ```bash\n  grep -n \"deliveryDrainCooldownUntil\\|DELIVERY_DRAIN_COOLDOWN_MS\\|skippedInProgress\" dist/monitor-polling.runtime-CVH4WvuC.js\n  grep -n \"skippedInProgress\" dist/delivery-queue-DnsUuJAM.js\n  ```\n\n- **Evidence after fix:** terminal output from the patched build:\n\n  The cooldown guard is active in the production Telegram polling runtime:\n\n  ```console\n  $ grep -n \"deliveryDrainCooldownUntil\\|DELIVERY_DRAIN_COOLDOWN_MS\\|skippedInProgress\" dist/monitor-polling.runtime-CVH4WvuC.js\n  476:const DELIVERY_DRAIN_COOLDOWN_MS = 3e4;\n  552:#deliveryDrainCooldownUntil = 0;\n  618:if (Date.now() < this.#deliveryDrainCooldownUntil) return;\n  637:if (drainResult.skippedInProgress > 0 && drainResult.drained === 0) this.#deliveryDrainCooldownUntil = Date.now() + DELIVERY_DRAIN_COOLDOWN_MS;\n  ```\n\n  The delivery queue correctly tracks skipped-in-progress entries:\n\n  ```console\n  $ grep -n \"skippedInProgress\" dist/delivery-queue-DnsUuJAM.js\n  559:skippedInProgress: 0\n  575:skippedInProgress: 0\n  579:result.skippedInProgress += 1;\n  ```\n\n  Line 618 is the early-return guard: when a previous drain found all entries already in-flight, the session skips further drain attempts for 30 seconds (30000ms = 3e4). Line 637 sets the cooldown only when `skippedInProgress > 0 && drained === 0`, so normal drains that successfully recover entries do not trigger the cooldown. Line 579 in the delivery queue increments the counter for each entry already claimed by `withActiveDeliveryClaim`.\n\n- **Observed result after fix:** The compiled production code at `dist/monitor-polling.runtime-CVH4WvuC.js:618` short-circuits drain attempts during the cooldown window. The condition at line 637 ensures the cooldown only activates when every matched entry was already being recovered (all skipped, none drained), preventing the every-30s re-entry loop described in #89953 while preserving normal drain behavior for genuinely new entries.\n- **What was not tested:** Live Telegram send stall scenario requiring a real Telegram bot with network conditions that cause 129s+ stalls. The cooldown duration (30s) was chosen to match the polling interval; production tuning may adjust it.\n\nCloses #89953\n",
        "branch": "fix/telegram-reconnect-drain-reentry-89953",
